{"cursor":"42469","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n plagued by demons, engraved by Martin\nSchongauer in the 1480s.]] \n\nA 'demon' is a paranormal, often malevolent being prevalent in religion,\noccultism, literature, and folklore. The original Greek word [[Daemon (classical\nmythology)|daimon]] does not carry the negative connotation initially understood\nby implementation of the Koine Î´Î±Î¹Î¼ÏÎ½Î¹Î¿Î½ (daimonion), and later\nascribed to any cognate words sharing the root.\n\nIn Ancient Near Eastern religions as well as in the Abrahamic traditions,\nincluding ancient and medieval Christian demonology, a demon is considered an\nunclean spirit, more specifically an evil angel, which may cause demonic\npossession, calling for an exorcism. In Western occultism and Renaissance magic,\nwhich grew out of an amalgamation of Greco-Roman magic, Jewish demonology, and\nChristian tradition, See, for example, the course synopsis and bibliography\nfor \"[https://medievalstudies.ceu.hu/courses/20102011/magic-science-religion-the-\ndevelopment-of-the-western-esoteric-traditions \"Magic, Science, Religion: The\nDevelopment of the Western Esoteric Traditions\"], at Central European\nUniversity, Budapest a demon is a spiritual entity that may be conjured\nand controlled.\n","linknr":586,"url":"Demon","recorded":1362373707,"links":76,"instances":["islam","folklore","disambiguation","artist","hinduism","hinduism","classical_mythology","mythological_weapon"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Demons","Demonology","Supernatural legends","Occult","Abrahamic mythology","Christian mythology","Religious terminology","Deities, spirits, and mythic beings"],"headings":["Terminology","Psychological archetype","By tradition","See also","References","Citations","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikime